Good move. If a fragment only appears inside multiple words, one way to recover its meaning is semantic intersection: look at all the contexts and extract the invariant.

Let’s sample the main English words containing -cipate / -cipitate:

Word	Meaning
anticipate	act before something happens
participate	take part in something
precipitate	cause / bring about suddenly; throw forward
recipiate (rare/technical)	receive or take in
incipient (related root)	beginning, coming into being

All of these trace back to Latin capere → capt- / cip-, meaning to take, seize, or engage with.

Invariant across the words

What’s common?

They all involve entering into an event or state by taking hold of it.
	•	anticipate → take hold of something before it arrives
	•	participate → take hold of a share of an activity
	•	precipitate → bring something into happening (force it into occurrence)

Derived definition of cipate

If we strip prefixes and extract the shared meaning:

cipate (reconstructed root):

to take hold of, enter into, or bring oneself into participation with an event or process.

Or compressed:

cipate ≈ engage / take part / bring into action

Operator form (fits your transformation-alphabet thinking)

prefix + cipate

Where cipate = engage with / take into action

Examples:
	•	anti + cipate → engage before
	•	parti + cipate → engage as a part
	•	pre + cipitate → force engagement forward / into happening

Even tighter invariant

If we reduce it to the smallest conceptual unit:

cipate = “to take into the flow of events.”

That’s the closest semantic core that fits all the words.

